ldn't have nothing to do with her. Me father was working regular. And - they said it was up to me father to try and - alter her. Not ill using her, as he did. He was a brute, my father was Well - they asked him and asked him 'til they were fed up. And - s
o - they took no notice. And she kept at me - me granny lived across the road, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Newcastle Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 they lived, and - there was just - me mother's mother and her step father. And the kept on a - a chip shop. Mind you she did some business. And my mother couldn
't rest, I'd peel potatoes and I'd pull mother out of it, you know. 'Cos she thought too much about drink. But her mother - her - her mother didn't - have - have drink, she used to have half a pint of a night time and that was all. And when I was older I 
u
sed to - fetch it from the next door, the public. The Bridge Inn. And then it got bombed while the war was on. But me mother wouldn't leave the drink alone, and then me father, he drank heavy and - it was when publics were open from eleven o'clock in the 
m
orning, but I don't mean - six o'clock in the morning they were open, 'til eleven at night. Yes, it's true. He - he lived there. And me mother did too. Well us children - every child she had, she had them, and we looked after 'em. I'll have the kids and y
ou must look after 'em, sort of thing, well that's what she used to say. And - except when they were bad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
So really even if you got new clothes off the tally man then they didn't sort of stay there very long?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 No. Oh they didn't stop - stay in the
 house, they were taken the next morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Would they be left in the pawn shop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Well they were left, yes, she'd run out. She'd lost 'em and she got that money - she'd got them to pay for then. Everything. And of course things was cheaper then than they are now. But - when you come to look at it it's just the same really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 What about shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Oh shoes, I never had no new shoes, if I did - I never wore 'em. I remember - there was - you know, when I got older - and used to sit - oh well, we'l
l go up Picadilly walking, after chaps you - well, lads then. And - I'd got no shoes to put on. So I went up the entry to this - elderly woman. And I said to her, I said - her name was Mrs Littler, she was a boatee. You know, worked on the canal. But she 
u
sed to come home every so often. And - of course you could get some - a goat - to elephant off her, you know what I mean? And - I asked her if she'd got a pair of shoes - cheap. I said, em mum - me mum had sent me. I said, what - now what size do you take
?
 Oh I said, I don't know. I didn't, I didn't know what size shoes I took. 'Cos I wore anybody's, see. As long as they - they went on me feet that was it. So her said, well come on, try these on. Tried them on and I said, oh they're just my fit. I said, bu
t
 - I haven't got any money to pay for 'em. She said well you're mother'll pay for 'em. Oh, I said, she won't. I said - shall I tell me mum - me mother as - you've give 'em to me, and I'll pay you - so much, every week? Do you know how much it was every we
e
k. Guess. Threepence. 'Course they were only second hand shoes she had. And - threepence a week and - and I paid her for 'em. And then - I had a costume, black, oh and I did like this costume. I wore it once. I bought it on the Saturday. And I'd got to pa
y
 for this costume. Mind you it was five shillings. Second hand, not the same person. The boatee woman. And - charged me five shilling and I said to her I said - I'll give you half this week and half next, the other like. She said, it's all right. Well - I
 had the costume. I put it on on the Sunday night. These shoes as - as I'd off her, I blacked 'em, with the old fashioned blacking. I can see the shoes and there was - costume after. She'd pawn your vest off your back. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 She would get clothes off a tally man, not second hand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Oh - bedding, in galore - she's had to go up the pawn shop when I was fourteen, in them days. And then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Pawn shops seem to have done a thriving business round here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Oh - not round here. Yes, in - in - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Shelton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}.
 Oh every Monday morning, used to go with prams - loaded up. Parcels under your arms, best road you could carry them. Yes, them were the days. And I did say - I said, well - the first time as I can get married, I said, I'll have none of this. Drink. No. A
nd it's a funny thing - haven't. But we've had a drink me and Mr Wilton, but we've known how far to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
The next bit is about the kind of help your dad would give your mother in the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 None.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 The cleaning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Well, done by the - children. Me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Cooking, did your mum do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Oh, me mother did the cooking. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Washing up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 I did it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Would your dad make the fires?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 He wouldn't. No. Come on, get some coal on this fire. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 What about decorating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 O
h that was done less or little - could be done. He never did no decorating.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 So really he didn't do anything in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
He didn't do nothing, no. No. It's with me mother or - or us when we got older you know. But me mother did - didn't do anyt
hing. Me mother didn't, mother was proper helpless. She wasn't ill. But she wouldn't do it. As long as she'd got us you see. We was - we used to say we was old fashioned family, because - each one of us - had to do something, clean, scrub and - mind you i
t wasn't polishing in them days No. Oh, elbow grease.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 What did your job used to be then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Mm? Oh well I - one used to wash the dishes. And scrub the table. Inside and out. The legs. You've seen this light furniture, as is - is about now? Well it w
as like that, when it was scrubbed, you know, light. We had a wooden squab, that' the sofa, with two arms on, all wood. No upholstering. And - one of use used to have to scr - well, I used to have to - scrub it. 'Course me and me brother, the eldest, Fred
, we - us two you see. The others used to go and fetch - coal from the coal yard, a quart of coal. They - they were outside playing, oh we weren't allowed to go out. No. Me and Fred used to be in the house. Fred used to be working. Down - 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Gasyard Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} there
. In the clay. Then he'd come home and started to - clean up. Saturdays and Sundays he used to - he used to clean the floors up and I used to get it all ready for him. And he used to clean the floors.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 That would be Fred?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 That's Fred, the oldest. Oh no, not me dad. Hm. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
How much part did your dad take then in bringing up the children, would he bath you or undress you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 No. He didn't do anything, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 He considered that a woman's job?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Well he - he - that's what he thought
 I suppose, but - no. He never put his hand nothing. My father didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
You've already told me that the older children had to help out with the younger ones
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Oh - yes. Yes. All of us. We all had to do something in - as they got older. But - me - b
rother and me we always used to be together you know, until he went in the Army. But he went in the Army under age. And he'd been working about - three weeks at this place, bank at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
Street}}Short Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, in the clay, the red clay. So - he brought this wages home. Fat
her says to me mother - Lizzie - what wages does Fred give you? So much. Well supposed to turn 'em all - all up see. But he used to bring this wage packet. Well he took a shilling out of it. The first week. He didn't take the second shilling. The next wee
k
. No. He went down to the firm, inquired - me father did, how much he was getting. It was right all but the shilling. He wanted for him - to come home, me father did - and he give him the biggest hiding - well - I - he struck that hard I thought he'd kill
ed him, I did. You know, he hit him that much. So on the Monday - in the middle of the week like}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14033997\charrsid10703177  it}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177  was, he says - Lal, he says, I'm not going to stay at home. I said, why, where are you going? He says, I'm going in the Army, I'm joining the Army. Oh, I sai
d, don And do you know, with him going in the Army, which he did, he joined up, he said he was older than what he was, he went all through the war without a scratch. That was in -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 The 14/18 war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Yes. Something of that, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 How old would he be then when he joined up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Oh - sixteen. Because they left school early in them days you know. He joined up when he was sixteen, well he wasn't old enough - at sixteen. But he went. And - but when he come home, after the war - my father didn't 
say a word to him. No. But he never encouraged me brother to do anything. He - never said that you haven't go to do this, you haven't got to do that, oh no. Because I think - then he'd learnt a hell of a lot when he was in the Army.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 He wouldn't be somebody to be pushed around?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
No, no, the good hidings as he's had. And then of course when - I - I was old I was working - I used to have to come home before I had - before -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 When did you leave school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Thirteen. When I was thirteen. They wer
e glad to get shot of me. They were. Because - I was that hardened, you know what I mean? Having these good hidings, and - I had plenty of food mind you. But it was rough. No sitting down to the table with a - you know - hm - knife and fork and all that, 
oh no.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 How did you used to have your meals then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Oh - on your knee. Yes. Bread. You know. It was only Sundays you had a bit of dinner on a plate. Mm. When I come to think of it. Then - and now. I can't believe it. You know what I mean? I - I cou
ldn't - I can't believe it, to think as parents could be - like they were. I'm not saying all parents, but mine - particularly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Were you expected to go to bed at a certain time in your schooldays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Any time after {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}
{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 10}}}ten o'clock{\*\xmlclose}.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Was that when the pubs came out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Well I had to stop and look after the - children, you know - and the house.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Your mum would go out to drink then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Oh - yes. Yes. And then you could go - you could go - drowned yourself after she come in. She wouldn't bother. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 So really your mum didn't look after the bed times for the other kids?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 All the kids looked after themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Used to have to go and make their beds. Put the children to bed. Them as were in bed first had the best - lay out. 'Cos they were round beds in them days you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 What do you mean round beds?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Well - boys and girls all together. In one bed. Top and bottom, you know. Well you don't see that today, not - well I've not seen it for years and years. But I suppose there is you know. Mm. Poverty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Thinking about the time you were at school who were you sharing the bed with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Oh I was sharing with the lads and the wen - the girls, we used to say wenches you know, lads and wenches. Used to be me, Maudie and 
Nance at the top. Fred - the three others at the bottom. Then the others in the little - spare - in the little room. You could sit on the window sill and put your feet on the - then ent - the entry floor, you know. If we wanted - run away or anything of t
hat, and yet there was nothing like that - in them days. No. We could have gone through the window and they wouldn't have missed us. Oh no, we - it seems as though they - we were glued there. Gouknow.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Better the devil you know I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Yes. An
d it wouldn't have you standing on the front doorstep talking. To anybody. Come in. And he'd shut the door - shut the front door. Get off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
How were the rest of the bedrooms used then, you had the six of you in one room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Do you mean - oh they were -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 And three in the other room, you had two other bedrooms?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
There was - the room was - all us as used to sleep in, the long bedroom it was. Then there was a little - square room, at the back. That was where the other lads slept. And then there 
was - who was in the other room, me mother and father, that was four rooms. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
We've talked about bathing arrangements, it was a zinc bath, how often did you have a bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Once a week. We were lucky if we got one then. 'Cos there was - the hous
e - oh the house was full all the time. You know what I mean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Did you used to have clean clothes to put on when you had a bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Oh yes. Yes. Oh yes, we weren't - dirty or nothing, oh no, no. By gum no, nothing like that. No, they were - rough. There were clean clothes but they were rough. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
You've already told me a bit about meals, where would your family usually eat? Did they eat in the kitchen or keep the front room for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Well - in the kitchen. Yes. We lived in the kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Were there any occasions when you would eat in the front room? What about Christmas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Oh - oh no, never kept - mother never kept no christenings up. No, it was - all one thing all the time. The same, you know, day in, day out, except for - if there was a funeral or anything of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 But all the eating would be done in the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Mm. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 What kind of cooking arrangements did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Hangers and tin bonnet. You mean for cooking. In front of the fire, hangers and tin bonnet,
 the old fashioned grates you know. Nothing like these. And - of course there was no gas stoves then. And - it was - the lamp. There was no gas. It was when I - left school and - worked - well I was working - when they started putting gas - in the houses.
 
And they used to put the gas - whatsits over the shelf, and every time - me father was in a temper, he used to - bang the cupboard door agen the shelf, you know, for the shelf was high up, and - used to knock the mantle off. Mantle off the - oh yes, he wo
uld - yes, there you are, he was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 When was breakfast eaten?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Well any time. When you could get it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 What time did your dad leave to go to work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Oh you didn't - we didn't have proper breakfast times you know. No, his time - when I was a girl - I used to have to go and stand in a queue - along by {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Hanley{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 there the bakery, for a loaf. Used to give you a little bit over, you know, to make weight. To - and this was on the war was on. Mm. I've eat the pieces they've give me on the top of th
e bread. When I've come back, where's the piece gone off here? He hasn't give it me. Good hiding. Of course I used to - I - I lost a lot of good hidings, because - you know what I mean - I was hardened to 'em. And then - if I wanted to go out anywhere I u
s
ed to have to - put me things the back of the lavatory door. Becore I could go and then I used to have to sneak out. Where are you going? I'm going - lavatory. Well I knew - when I was going out as I should have a good hiding when I - you know. But - I'd 
got to be in early. Not like they are today. Oh when I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
But really mealtimes there weren't any set times, people would just come in and eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
They'd come in and - get hold of a piece and that was it. But you could have as much as you wanted. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 You could have it if it was there but often there wasn't very much there?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Can you remember what did you usually have to eat and drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
We used to have tea without milk. Sometimes we had tinned milk. Yes, this condensed milk.
 And I - I wouldn't - if there was any about now I wouldn't - I wouldn't buy a tin. I wouldn't. We used to have jars. What they used to make the tea in. So much tea, so much water. No milk in. Now, going to school this was And it was snowing, or raining o
r something or other. Just the same, it didn't matter. We got - wore anybody's shoes. Holes in 'em.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 You say jars, you mean you would drink out of jars?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Yes. Jam jar - you know, these - stone jars. Pound jars they were. We all used to have one. No table cloth on the table. Oh no. And I'm not making it worse than what it should - what it would be. Oh yes, quite true.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Would Saturdays and Sundays be any different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Oh no, no, Saturday was the same as Sunday. We used to have - potatoes and -
 vegetables on a Sunday. And I'd got to fetch them in. And - used to have a - a rabbit. We used to take a carrier bag - up to Ewbanks's. Not this Ewbanks's up here, not - not this one but - relation to 'em. And - ox - oxford - 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Oxford Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And I used to ha
ve to go up there, get this rabbit and vegetables, I used to get as much - for one and sox - for all of us, all the family of us, and Christmas time I used to go up and used to get the carrier bag full. Fruit. Cehap you know. But - you - you hadn't got to
 
touch anything. Keep your fingers out of it. Yes. And they could tell if you'd had any of it you know. Yes. Oh - oh I used to get it, but - well - 'til 1921. I didn't do no couring. Only again the front door. This is when I was - going to get married to m
e
 first husband, I - and I wasn't sure, you know. So - I must have stood a bit too long. Comes in. And - me father wouldn't leave no light on you know. Turn the lamp out. No light. All the - the gas. Who was that? Oh. He could hear you - he could - I don't
 
- he used to - somehow - know what you were saying, you know. And I - I used to say under me breath, who do you think it is. Then he used to shout down, yes - you'll know who it is if I come down then stairs. Mm. But any road - I'd just pull me shoes off,
 
and I run down the entry. I was working. I run down the entry out of his road, 'cos I - I hear him get out of bed and - I thought to myself, well - he might as well hit - hit me outside, as - as hit me in here because - well I knew - I knew what he was, a
n
d he - with having long hair, see, I used to have it in plaits and at night time I used to undo it. He caught me. The bottom of the entry. And he swung me round looking - right up again the wall. Well the wall shook. I've more than enough from you, he sai
d
, and I'll murder you. I never used to answer him back. Up the entry I went. Came after me. Hm. I went in, and he said, why have you stayed out so late? I said, I wasn't outside, I was agen the front door. Don't you use your cheek to me. You know? I said,
 
I was agen the front door, and I've not strayed away from there. But I had. I went in the entry. Of course - I got meself in trouble. Over the girl. And - I went on, I was nearly three months. Of course - nobody knew, I never told anybody. But me father g
u
essed. Me mother didn't, and yet me mother had all them children. He said to my mother, Liz - there's something wrong with her. She said, oh Fred, she said no there isn't. He says, I know there is. 'Cos me mother didn't get up in the morning with me, but 
h
e did. And I said once to me mother I said, does me father ever go sleep? You know? Not thinking anything. Says, of course he goes to sleep, why? Well, I said, he always seems to be awaking So he says - and I said - she said to me she said - they, somethi
n
g wrong with you? I thought to myself, well - if I say no - I said, well - yes. So simple. You know So I thought I was. She said, you're father told me. Your father knew. I said, well how was it you didn't know then? And me father did. She said, well, he 
c
ould tell in the mornings. You wouldn't have no tea, see, that's what give me away. And then there was sometimes I - things was alight, I wouldn't - didn't want 'em, see. I said, but oh I'm getting married. I didn't know whether I was getting married - or
 buried. I really didn't. And I would rather been buried - as get married. And - I got married. The bridegroom \{BLANK\} I was - I really - I was, I was real soft.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Did your mum make her own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 You went out to buy it didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Did she make jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Did she bottle fruit or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 She wasn't very housework fond was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Oh no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 She didn't make pickles or wine or anything like this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 No. Oh no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 They didn't brew beer for the family, they just went out and bought it?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 That's right. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 What about a garden, did you have a garden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 No, there was no gardens. Not there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 No allotments?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 No. He didn't have no gardens round there did you Ben, not round that road.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 You didn't grow your own vegetables or stuff like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
No, I think that's what - people really wanted in them days. It should - I don't know, he - I don't think as - 'course there was a good many round that road you know
 as - devil to the children and to the wives, 'course my mother used to get laid on every week. Every weekend. Mm. And yet me father was that particular. Oh the - clean, oh yes, he was clean. He was. Only you see - you couldn't put a curler - curling pin 
n
or nothing in your hair. We couldn't - if you washed your hair thought he'd say, where are you going? I'm not going anywhere, I've just washed me hair. Don't forget, no curlers in. No plaiting. He wouldn't allow you - to plait your hair. Even me mother di
dn't. He wouldn't let me mother curl her - curl her hair nor nothing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 He had strong views on certain things?
