\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 No. No. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Did you belong to any trade union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Well I - I don't remember paying union.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Quite a lot of women didn't did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Not in the - them days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Did you feel that employers and workers had got the same interests?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Oh I was comfortable there. Yes I was. I liked 'em - I liked 'em all.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Did you feel there were any sort of great divisions of interest amongst the workers? Or did you feel everybody was pulling in the same way?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Oh they all did their share. They got to - oh yes, they'd all got good jobs. Easy jobs. Walking round a - the works, straightening the place up, you know, and we'd got a woman - Mrs Vegas as used to ge
t us - a cup of tea ready for - you know, in the morning after - about eleven o'clock we used to have a cup of tea, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Would you say that moving into full time work then changed your attitude to life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Well it did. Yes. But - it didn't alter
 me parents. No. You know, they - used to - think me things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Your horizons were broadened a bit when you moved out into a job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Mm. I got good money, and then - I'd - I'd - left there, I'd been left a good while, and I was working for Mrs Molyneu
x, the public. The public house at the end of the street. And - that was where I used to go in - you know, but I was single then. But I didn't have - you know - and - she asked me if I'd like - to work there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 How old were you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 About nineteen. I'd be about - nineteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 So we're above 1918 then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Yes. And - That was - really the last - the last good job as I had. I was -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 You went to the Cromo job after you'd been to Molynexu?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 No. No I didn't. No, no, I'd left - no, I didn't
 go back there. No, wait a minute, wait a minute. No. The wagon works - two gaffers from there - from out of the office, and Mrs Molyneux said to me she says, Florrie, she said - you've got to get used to this bar work, so she says, come along, she says, 
a
nd I'm going to show you - what to do. She told me. I - I was very quick at picking anything up you know. And - she says, now take these in, so much. Well when they spotted me you know - well - I'll be hanged, if it isn't our Florrie. What are you doing h
e
re? Barmaid. Oh no, I'm not a barmaid, I'm a cleaner. I said, I live here. Why? Do you? I said, yes, I said, I only live along the street there. Well, three doors from the pub, and - he says, do you like it? I said, I - oh, I said, what, I said, I wouldn'
t give it up for the world. I said. He said, well I - look - he said, I've got some money for you. I've got some for {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}Victoria{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Oh I said, she will - I was glad - for her you know, I said, oh she will be pleased. He said, well aren't you? Yes, I said, yes, I
 said, how much? Oh, he said, I'm not going to tell you, it's going to be a surprise. He says, so what will you - oh, he says, will you come down tomorrow. So of course I said, well I'll have to ask Mrs Molyneux. So - I'd always done me work, it wasn't a 
b
ig public house you know, and I'd always done me - housework, well I could please myself what I did, in the afternoon, and - I said, Mrs Molyneux. I said - could I down - go down to the wagon works She says, you're not leaving me? No, I said, I'm not leav
i
ng, I said, I've got some money coming to me and I'm going down after it tomorrow. Her says - yes, of course you can go. Her says - what you going to do with it? Oh, I said, I don't know what to do, I said, because - if me mother ever finds out as I've ha
d
 it - oh I don't know what'll happen. Do you know, as my mother knew - what I was going to have - my mother did. I didn't say nothing to her. So when I went - home like - for the weekend 'cos I used to go - and stop at home for the weekend see after I'd d
o
ne me cleaning at Molyneux. For so many hours like 'til they opened at night time, and - well beer was short - in them days. And they were closed so many days a week, so many nights. So she said, well I don't see why - I should let you stay in Florrie, sh
e
 says - if you like, her says, you can go and spend an hour at - your mother's. I said, all right Mrs Molyneux. But I daresn't got to the pictures you know, not without - oh no. And - I went home and mother says - I've heard as you've picked some money up
 
at the wagon works. Well I hadn't give it her, you know what I mean, not then. But I'd still got it. And - I'd got a little handbag, and I cherished that handbag, I did, it was one as she gave me. And I - I said, well, I've still got it. Said, well come o
n
. Let's have it. That's how she talked to me. Instead of saying, well aren't you going to give me so much of it, help me with the home like. It would have been a different thing, but she said, come on, let's have it, come on. What - what she did with it w
a
s go in the pub at night time, 'til it had all gone. And - I could have tried. I could. So when I went home - to Mrs Molyneux at home like, it was like home to - really you know to me, and I went and - she says, to me, what's - what's wrong Miss - Florrie
?
 I said - I know - I were crying again. She says, what - what's wrong? Tell me, you can tell me can't you? I said, yes, I can tell you. I don't know what you'd think, I said, about - me or - I said, or - me mother. Her said, I know what I think about your
 
mother, her says, but you, her says, I think if you'd got a - a train and went miles and miles away from 'em, that's what she said. Oh, I said, I couldn't do that Mrs Molyneux I said, oh they'd find me. She says, well - and has your mother taken that mone
y
 off you? I said, yes, she has. Every penny. She never give me a cent out of it. My mother didn't. And it was pounds. In a big envelope. 'Cos the chap said to me, the manager, he said - now you two, he says, what are you going to do with your money, and t
h
at was to me. I said, I'm going to buy a piano, I don't know whatever made me think of that. I said, I'm going to buy a piano. He says, and I hope you play it. He said to me. Oh, I said, yes, I'll play it all right. Said to Vic, what are you going to do w
i
th your money Vic? Well, she said, I've got plenty to do with mine, her said, I've got a little boy to keep you know and - she was in lodgings you know, just round the corner from us. I felt sorry for that - person, I did. But believe me when I saw her, l
ook you, I could have dropped through the earth.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
You continued to live at home most of the time after you left school didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
There was this period when you lived at Molyneux but you were still near to home?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 You were hardly really away?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Did starting full time work change your relationship with your parents?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 You were still expected to help out at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 And hand over all your cash?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 That was it. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Did your brothers and sisters treat you any differently?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Oh used to shout at one another. We got older.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Things didn't change much after you went to work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Did you spend your Sunday any differently?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Mm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Did you spend Sunday any differently?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 No. Oh no, Sunday, no, Sunday was the same as every other day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Did you take any interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Once you started work did you spend your spare time in any different ways, or was it just the same as it had been before?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 No. Come day, go day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Did you go out in the evenings, were you allowed to go out?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
No. And if I sneaked out. They wouldn't let me go. I used to have a good did in every time I come in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 If you sneaked out where would you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Oh I used to to go to the skating rink. You know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Where was the skating rink then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
In Hanley. Where the Palace - used - I don't know whether the palace - is the Palace still there? Oh. Well it was before the Palace took over, it was a skating rink. I've had many a hour there. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 You enjoyed skating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Oh yes, and - mm. Yes. Well anyway - I used to love going. I used to go and I - my father knew. 'Cos they weren't proper good shoes as I wore, and if it was raining, well - th
e - the sakets used to fetch near the sole off. Used to make - where the skates used to be fastened. Me father -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 How much would it cost to go skating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Sixpence. Threepence your skates and threepence to go in. And we used to -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 You could only go once with your pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
That's right. Every night. I could have gone - different places, you know, but - oh didn't have the money. And I used to - when I come back my father'd say, where have you been? Well I've been - I've been walking roun
d with so and so. He just looked down, of course he used to call me a liar.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Well you were weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
I was. A real good liar. Bang. True. Not one. Two or three. So - as time went on - well - I come to get in with this Charlie. Ooh, I hated him. I was married - eight years all told to him, but I was parted four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 He was somebody you met at the skating rink then was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 No. He was a neighbours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 He used to come in to see your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Yes. He did. I didn't find out until it was
 too late. And of course - I got meself in trouble. And - he didn't want to marry me. But it was me father's made him. Me mother bought the wedding ring. I wore clothes as other people had wore, to get married in at the registry. It didn't cost him a penn
y because he'd got no money. I was lucky to get married but I thought - oh - I'm getting married, it doesn't matter, you know. I'm getting away from home, that's what I thought. But oh dear. I'd gone out of the frying pan into the fire.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 After you left school did you make any different friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Well I didn't have no friends, really, no. It was all - around. You know. The girls were getting older and - used to talk to one another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Did you feel that your parents were interested in meeting your 
friends? Did they want to know who you were with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Yes, if they were going to get anything. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
But they weren't sort of class some people as bad company and want to keep you away from them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Well - one - when she found out - as I was - sne
aking out with - Charlie - Charlie Worrall his name was - 'course she didn't know - at first, but the fellow as I should have married - I didn't - well I - I liked him, but I don't know why, something was - pulling me back off him sort of thing and he onl
y
 lived next door but one to us, and his name was Bill Taylor. But he was ever such a nice fellow. Always dressed up and all that, and he used to come in our house, two and three times a week. It was to see me. And - it was on the Friday night about a fort
n
ight - and I was sneaking out with Charlie Worrall see. And he says to me he says, look - he says, don't think I haven't seen you - Lol, he always called me Lol, he says, I - I have seen you, he says, but - I don't want to come between you, he says, but I
 know very well as he won't do you good. Oh, I said, you will? Just like that you know. He said, well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 You weren't at a loss for a quick word were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
I'm not - oh no. And I was blackleading the grate to one - on the Friday night and I was blac
kleading the grate in the kitchen. Well our door was never shut. And he walked in. And of course, he said to me he said, look - I tell you what Lol. I said, look, it isn't as I wouldn't go out with you Bill, I said, but I don't want to give Charlie up, I 
s
aid. He said, well, he said - why won't you give him up? Are you afraid? No. And I wished to God I had have done. You know. At the time. And he said - he says to me he says, look me he says, I'll tell him if you don't like to tell him. Oh he said, I could
 
tell him. I said, no doubt you would. I said, but no, I'll tell him. He says, you don't see him 'til closing time and you're stuck in this house. You're waiting for him. I know. So any way one word brought on another and he said - tell me - why won't - wh
y
 don't - don't you like me? Yes, I said, I'm very fond of you Bill, I said, but - I can't court two of you. Mash them Can't mash two of you. He says - that - surely to goodness he said I can do better than him. I said, yes, no doubt you could - would. I s
a
id, but why - why do you want - to take me out? Why? I knew things were wrong and I knew things were right. But I hadn't got the sense enough to - you know what I mean, to grip. So I said - look Bill, I said, you are dressed up. I'll put my shoes on, look
,
 from underneath the sofa. You take me out, I said, with a pair of shoes like this. You take me out You're dressed up. Me. He says, look, clothes don't matter to me. It's what I can do for you. Oh, I said, yes. No, he said, I don't mean - I don't mean any
t
hing personal. But he didn't say that word, but that's - you know. He says, look, I'll tell you what. If you make your mind up, he says, we'll go out, tomorrow, that was Saturday, we'll go out, he says, and I'll buy you a coat. And shoes. Oh, I thought, h
e
llo. I said, Bill - do you know what'll happen? If I have a coat, and new shoes? No. I don't know what'd happen. I said well I do, and you're not going to waste your money on me. No, I said. He said, why what would happen? I said - he said, well I'll tell
 
you what Lol, he said, your mother knows. That I'm after you. Your mother knows that. I said, oh well me mother's never said nothing. She hadn't. She wouldn't say nothing to me you know. So any road he said - will you do - will you - go with me. Look Bill
, forget it will you No. I said, now - all the tea in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}China{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 - wouldn't - drive me. You'll repent. Well - something come over me, about - oh I - he used to come in - other nights like again, used to call - as he were going -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 How old were you when this was going on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Oh - I was going out with Charlie Worrall then, I'd be twenty. Nearly twenty-one. And - he said to me, he says, you'll repent it. I said, oh no, I - I won't. He said, you marry him, he says, are you getting married? I - I said, I don't 
know whether I'm getting married or no, he's never asked me, you know. So anyway - he said, well I'll see you again. I said, all - all right Bill, goodnight, and off he used to go so - I don't know what come over me, and I decided - to go out with him. Bu
t
 I didn't get the chance. No. Like the week after, and it was on the Saturday night, and I stood by the front door. I were looking out for him you know oh I was definite, I was going to - say yes, I'll go out with you. He come and he said, hello Lol. Hell
o Bill. Off he went. And he turned round the corner and I thought he's going - to have a drink before he goes out. So he went and had this drink and then he - I saw him - 'cos I stood - still stood on the doorstep, and he - he went along 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Cemetery Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And - he always wore his hat, a blocker he used to wear, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15404464\charrsid10703177 blower}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
 end, and he always used to tilt it a bit you know and he - he - he had used to look ever so nice. Ben knows him very well. And - I waited for him. And it was on a Saturday night, it was summer wea
ther. And this young woman, she'd got a red coat on and a hat, little round hat, to match, red. 'Course - this Bill Taylor and her come walking along the street and she was linking him. And believe me, I coloured up like a beetroot - before they - they co
m
e - you know to pass me. He said, hello - Lol. Hello Bill. I went in, I shut that door. And I - I cried. And I thought well - perhaps it's somebody as he's - a relation or something of that I said, thought to myself. So when - on the Sunday morning - he s
t
ood by the door and I was sweeping our fronts. I felt as though I could have hit him with the brush you know. I went to him - hey - he thought I was going to hit him with it, honest. He said, hey - go steady with that brush. I said, why, do you think I wa
s
 going to hit you? I said, I feel as though I could. Yes? He says, you wouldn't be told would you. When I did want to take you out you wouldn't go. I said, of course I'd got excuse then. I said, no, I said, I didn't want to go out with you because you wer
e
 playing two - you'd have been playing two timer. I said, and I wasn't going to have that Bill. I said, that wasn't the first time as you'd seen her. Well he said, I - I'm not struck on her Lol, he says, but - then he says I've got to have somebody take m
e
 out. I said, ooh - ooh I said, yes, no doubt. He said well I'm afraid he said it's a bit too late now, he said - I've - I'm getting engaged to her. Good luck, I said. And I hope she has all the kids in the world, I said. And off I - I - I come with the s
w
eeping brush you know, and I never looked at him again. No I didn't. So Ben, he was working on a - on - Twyfords was it, and he - Bill saw him. He said aren't you - Ben Wilton. He said, I am. You're the one as married - Lol Coxon. Oh he said I've heard - 
h
e said - Ben said to him he said oh he said I've heard - I've heard Lol talk about you. He says, she was a proper fool - to herself. He said, I wanted to make a difference Ben, he says, but she wouldn't have it. No. I said, no, we've talked about him many
 a time. We have.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Did your parents expect you to come home for a certain time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 No. Certain time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 What time would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 The proper time - from work, about - half past five, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 So you were expected to come home and have a meal then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
Yes, if it was ready. I used to have to clean up or - scrub the table and - odd jobs before I'd anything to eat, and been to work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
What if you went out at night, would they expect you to be in a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Oh, as I got older.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 What time would they expect you to be in then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Well - they didn't know as I went to the skating rink until they found out.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 But if you were missing out of the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Oh yes. I used to have to be in the house - sitting there, if I got
 nothing do. When father come in. And if - I stopped out a little bit late and me father was working all night see - but they had me going down taking his supper. And I know what that was for. To keep me in, so as I shouldn't go out anywhere see, only for
 
take his supper. And - then when - well - I got in with him, Charlie and - things went wrong and - me father said what he'd do if - he didn't marry me. He asked me if I was getting married, I said, oh yes, of course I am, I said. But I didn't. I'd no idea
.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
You told me that in 1911 your dad would be working at the Deep Pit in Hanley, and he was what you described at a daytler?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Can you tell me what this was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Oh I don't now what a daytler is really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 But he worked down the pit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 And he had a certain number of men under him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Men - under him, yes. To get the coal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
And they were sort of paid wages in a block and your dad sort of shared out the money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Yes. That's right. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 We talked about the wa
shing being done, it would be done at home. Where would it be done, did you have a wash house outside?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
No. No. In the kitchen. 'Cos there was only parlour and kitchen. But summertime we did it in the yard. But I had to do that when I come home from work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 You talked about a pawn shop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 What was the name of the pawnshop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Oh, Commasoles. Broad Street. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Shelton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Oh dear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 We talked about your mum and dad and they were both fond of the drink?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Yes. Fond!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Did your dad have any views on your mother drinking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 I don't think it was right. It was her downfall.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Did your dad sort of try to stop her drinking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
No. No he didn't. He was getting his and he didn't care. But I never saw me dad tumble about, no matter how much drink he had. Or me mother. Oh yes. They were used to it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 
At one point you said when you were talking about how your mum came to start drinking that she was about forty when she started?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Yes, she did. Yes. Yes. That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10306935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Probably she was glossing over things a bit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5664013 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16718425\charrsid10703177 Yes, she was.
